 “It’s a painting that speaks for itself,” she added. “You just have to look at it — it’s full of expression, and you can see all of Picasso’s genius.” Previously, Sevestre-Barbé noted, the work had only been seen in a black-and-white photograph. “We couldn’t imagine from this photo that this painting was so colorful, so amazing, really.” Auctioneer Lucien said before the sale that the work was of huge interest across the globe. “It’s being talked about in all the world capitals with a strong art market, from the United States to Asia, and of course through all the major European markets,” he said.  Though selling above expectations, the work was far from the most expensive Picasso work sold at auction. In 2023, the artist’s famed “Femme à la montre” (“Woman with a Watch”) — portraying another muse, Marie-Thérèse Walter — sold for $139.4 million, the second most valuable Picasso sold at auction. The most valuable was $179.4 million, paid in 2015 for a version of “Les Femmes d’Alger” (“Women of Algiers”). ____ Associated Press writer Jocelyn Noveck contributed from New York.

